VERDICT: confirmed-but-no-uca
UCA: (none — see REASON)
REASON: Source trace confirms the bug: fatal.rs:172 unconditionally returns RecoveryAction::Ignore for (KernelPanic, Isr, test_mode=true), contradicting the module's documented FT2 invariant ("kernel panic is always non-recoverable", lines 28, 48). The classify ensures clause at lines 127-128 explicitly restricts FT2 to !self.test_mode — a spec-weakening, not a proof. lemma_panic_halts (line 251) is an "ensures true" stub so Verus never checks full FT2. The FFI replica at tests/differential_fatal.rs:31-41 mirrors the same bug (reason=4 in ISR+test_mode yields FATAL_ACTION_IGNORE), so the differential oracle passes in lockstep — classic proof/code drift. The existing fatal_kernel_panic_always_halts_production test (line 156) only pins test_mode=false, leaving the (reason=4, is_isr=1, test_mode=1) case unexercised. Downstream reachability is credible: zephyr/gale_fatal.c:141 gates the ASSERT(reason != K_ERR_KERNEL_PANIC) behind !CONFIG_TEST, making the Rust Ignore decision the sole gate under CONFIG_TEST. The dispatch is straight-line deterministic — no race, no hardware dependency, no caller-documented precondition violated. Finding is real and interesting. However, the Mythos procedure asks for a mapping into safety/stpa/ucas.yaml; that file does not exist. The only STPA artifact is artifacts/stpa.yaml which at lines 12-13 explicitly states that UCAs are out of scope for this initial revision (only L-1..L-3, H-1..H-6, SC-1..SC-6 are captured). No existing UCA covers the fatal-error controller. A new UCA is needed — e.g. "UCA-FATAL-1: Fatal-error controller provides Ignore recovery when reason=KernelPanic in ISR context under CONFIG_TEST, failing to halt after an unrecoverable fault." This in turn requires a new hazard ("H-7: kernel resumes execution after unrecoverable panic, defeating the fail-stop property") with a leads-to-loss link to L-1/L-2, and a new SC ("fatal path must always halt on KernelPanic, irrespective of CONFIG_TEST or ISR context"). Note: the oracle PoC was not executed because tmp-file creation was denied in this sandbox; however, the source trace is deterministic and leaves no branch ambiguity (fatal.rs:162-172 is a pure match with a single arm for the counter-shape), so the Verus-level counter-instance in the report is directly realisable by inspection.
